         <h1>Peter Boyle, 71, Is Dead; Roles Evoked Laughter and Anger </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Peter Boyle , who left the life of a monk to study acting and went on to become one of the most successful character actors of his time in films like '' Joe , '' '' Young Frankenstein '' and '' Monster 's Ball , '' then capped his career as the curmudgeonly father on the hit sitcom '' Everybody Loves Raymond , '' died on Tuesday evening in Manhattan . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 71 . <br><blue>3</blue>His death was announced by his publicist , Jennifer Plante . <br><blue>4</blue>She said Mr. Boyle , who lived in Manhattan , had suffered from multiple myeloma and heart disease . <br><blue>5</blue>Mr. Boyle received five Emmy Award nominations for his portrayal of the grouchy , wisecracking Frank Barone in nine seasons on '' Raymond . '' <br><blue>6</blue>But it was in dramatic roles that he emerged as a formidable presence on screen a quarter-century earlier -- a tall , bulky-framed , balding actor playing memorable characters like a drunken redneck ( '' Joe '' ) , a corrupt union leader ( '' F.I.S.T. '' ) and a savvy private eye ( '' Hammett '' ) . <br><blue>7</blue>Mr. Boyle could be convincingly chilling , so much so that he often ran the risk of being typecast . <br><blue>8</blue>When he appeared with Peter Falk in William Friedkin 's 1978 film '' The Brink 's Job , '' playing a gang member , Vincent Canby wrote in The New York Times that '' Mr. Boyle 's role is one that he could telephone in by this time . '' <br><blue>9</blue>But it was n't all thugs and gangsters . <br><blue>10</blue>In 1974 , in Mel Brooks 's film '' Young Frankenstein , '' he played the bumbling monster brought to life by Dr. Frankenstein 's addled grandson ( Gene Wilder ) . <br><blue>11</blue>At one point , Mr. Boyle 's monster , decked out in white tie and tails à la Fred Astaire , performed a nifty soft-shoe routine with Mr. Wilder while bellowing out the lyrics of Irving Berlin 's '' Puttin ' On the Ritz . '' <br><blue>12</blue>Mr. Boyle , who once admitted to being '' a little nutty , '' enjoyed his infrequent ventures into film comedy . <br><blue>13</blue>In '' Where the Buffalo Roam '' ( 1980 ) , a screen portrait of the freewheeling writer Hunter S. Thompson ( Bill Murray ) , he went happily wild as the writer 's carousing companion . <br><blue>14</blue>With members of the Monty Python troupe , he was part of a zany pirate crew in '' Yellowbeard '' ( 1983 ) . <br><blue>15</blue>And in '' The Dream Team '' ( 1989 ) , he played a mental patient fixated on Jesus . <br><blue>16</blue>His breakthrough , however , was no laughing matter . <br><blue>17</blue>He won the title role in the 1970 film '' Joe , '' about a hard-drinking , hate-filled factory worker who improbably joins forces with a murderous executive in a bloody war on hippies and the rest of the counterculture . <br><blue>18</blue>He was paid only $ 3,000 for the work , he later said , but he realized he had taken a giant step forward . <br><blue>19</blue>The role , he said at the time , seemed to have been made for him because he had grown up surrounded by people like Joe . '' <br><blue>20</blue>I knew the character so well that when it came to the actual shooting of the movie , I was worried that I would do a caricature , '' he said . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>The role</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>the title role</m_str> (17_3) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Manhattan</m_str> (1_70) 	<m_str>Manhattan</m_str> (4_9) 	<br><blue>3(1)</blue>: <m_str>his career</m_str> (1_49) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Boyle 's monster , decked out in white tie and tails à la Fred Astaire</m_str> (11_5) 	<m_str>the bumbling monster</m_str> (10_16) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>She</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his publicist , Jennifer Plante</m_str> (3_6) 	<br><blue>6(35)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (15_12) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>a monk to study acting and went on to become one of the most successful character actors of his time in films like '' Joe , '' '' Young Frankenstein '' and